body:
I need some help with the following integration/use of fundamental theorem of calculus: $\displaystyle x(t) =  \int_{0}^{t} \exp (-2s)a(s) \ ds$, where $a(x) = \left\{
     \begin{array}{lr}
       -1 & : t \in [0,1]\\
       1& : t \in (1, \infty)
     \end{array}
   \right.$ How should I simplify the integral?
